== 10th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 925 || || [[Egils Saga]] describes the expedition of Icelandic [[viking]]s Thorolf and [[Egill Skallagrímsson]] by the [[Route from Varangians to Greeks|Eastern route]] (''Austrvegr''), where they won much wealth and had many battles. In [[Courland]] they made a peace for half a month and traded with the men of the land.<ref>[https://books.google.lv/books?id=QGamTnbBrS4C&pg=PT122&lpg=PT122&dq=Egill+Skallagr%C3%ADmsson+Courland&source=bl&ots=9z8Wueb9Jt&sig=bE75yZsJux3b72KfhzSYTRun1cY&hl=lv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUktSI3Z7KAhXJBiwKHXP2CC8Q6AEIWTAI#v=onepage&q=Egill%20Skallagr%C3%ADmsson%20Courland&f=false Rev. W. C. Green. The Story of Egil Skallagrimsson: An Icelandic Family History of the Ninth ... Chapter 46]</ref> |- | 950 || || The Norse prince Ragnvald ([[Rogvolod|Rogvolod of Polatsk]]) came from overseas and subjugated [[hillfort]]s along the river of [[Daugava River|Daugava]]. His capital was established at [[Polatsk]]. |}
== 11th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | before 1100 || || The borders of the [[Balts|Baltic]] realms of [[Courland]], [[Semigallia]], [[Tālava]], [[Principality of Koknese|Koknese]] and [[Jersika]] (known as ''Lettia'') became settled. |}
== 12th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1106 || || [[Semigallians]] completely destroyed united armies of the sons of Prince [[Vseslav of Polotsk]] in the lowlands of [[Daugava River|Daugava]]. |- | 1111 || || [[Prince of Novgorod]] [[Mstislav Vladimirovich]] invaded eastern part of [[Tālava]] (Adzele) and [[Ugandi]]. |- | 1180 || || Prince [[Mstislav Rostislavich]] led the Novgorodians against the [[Latvians|Letts]] of [[Tālava]]. |- | 1184 || || The monk [[Saint Meinhard]] began missionary work among the [[Livonian people]]. |- | 1186 || || [[Saint Meinhard|Meinhard]] was appointed bishop of [[Livonia]] by the Pope. |- | 1198 || || Bishop [[Berthold of Hanover]] arrived at the mouth of the [[Daugava River]] accompanied by crusaders and was killed in battle with [[Livonian people|Livonians]]. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1199 || || [[Albert of Riga]] was elected the third bishop of [[Livonia]]. |- | || Pope [[Pope Innocent III|Innocent III]] proclaimed a second Baltic Crusade. |}
== 13th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1201 || || [[Albert of Riga|Albert]] founded [[Riga]] on the site of earlier Livonian settlement. |- | 1202 || || The [[Livonian Brothers of the Sword]] was founded by Bishop [[Albert of Riga|Albert]]. |- | 1206 || || The [[Livonian Brothers of the Sword|Brothers of the Sword]] and their [[Semigallians|Semigallian]] allies defeated the [[Livonian people|Livonians]] and [[Latgalians]]. |- | 1217 || || The [[Livonian Brothers of the Sword|Brothers of the Sword]] and their [[Livonian people|Livonian]] and [[Latgalians|Latgalian]] allies defeated the [[Estonians]] at [[Viljandi]]. |- | 1229 || || Bishop [[Albert of Riga|Albert]] died. |- | 1236 || || ''[[Battle of Saule]]'': The [[Livonian Brothers of the Sword|Brothers of the Sword]] were defeated in [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania|Lithuania]] by the combined forces of the Lithuanians and [[Semigallians]]. |- | 1242 || || [[Alexander Nevsky]] defeated the [[Livonian Order]] on [[Lake Peipus]]. |- | 1255 || || The [[Diocese|Bishopric]] at [[Riga]] was elevated to become the [[Archbishopric of Riga]]. |- | 1282 || || [[Riga]] became a member of the [[Hanseatic League]]. |}
== 14th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1378 || || The [[Livonian Order]] raided [[Upytė]], and another campaign threatened the Lithuanian capital in [[Vilnius]]. |}
== 15th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1422 || || A [[Livonia]]n ''[[Diet (assembly)|Diet]]'' first met. |- | 1452 || || The [[Livonian Order]] and [[Archbishopric of Riga]] began to rule jointly in [[Livonia]]. |- | 1481 || || [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Russia]] attacked [[Livonia]]. |}
== 16th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1501 || || The [[Livonian Order]], aided by [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania|Lithuania]], launched an attack on [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Russia]]. |- | 1502 || || [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Russia]] was defeated at the Battle of Lake Smolina near [[Palkino, Palkinsky District, Pskov Oblast|Palkino]]. |- | 1558 || || [[Ivan the Terrible]] launched an attack on [[Livonia]]. |- | 1561 || || ''[[Livonian War]]'': [[Livonia]] fell to [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania|Lithuania]]. |- | 1569 || || [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania|Lithuania]] and [[Kingdom of Poland (1385–1569)|Poland]] joined to form the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]]. [[Livonia]] became a joint domain administered directly by both realms. |}
== 17th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1629 || || The [[Peace of Altmark]] was reached, under which [[Swedish Empire|Sweden]] annexed [[Livonia]] and several [[Courland]] territories to [[Swedish Livonia]]. |- | 1689 || || The Old and New Testaments were published in [[Latvian language|Latvian]] translation by Pastor [[Ernst Glück]]. |- | 1700 || || ''[[Great Northern War]]'': A war began which involved the [[Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth]], [[Swedish Empire|Sweden]], and [[Tsardom of Russia|Russia]]. |}
== 18th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1710 || || [[Riga]] fell to the [[Tsardom of Russia|Russians]], though [[Courland]] remained under the control of the [[Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth]]. |- | 1721 || || ''[[Great Northern War]]'': The [[Treaty of Nystadt]] ended the war. |}
== 19th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1841 || || A famine occurred in [[Livonia]]. |- | 1873 || || The first [[Latvian Song and Dance Festival]] took place. |- | 1887 || || Russification measures began in the [[Baltic governorates]] of the [[Russian Empire]]. |}
== 20th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1905 || 13 January || [[Russian Empire|Russian]] army troops opened fire on demonstrators in [[Riga]], killing seventy-three and injuring two hundred people. |- | || A revolution took place in the [[Baltic region]] directed primarily against German landowners and [[Russian Empire|Russian]] autocracy. |- | 1914 || 1 August || ''[[World War I]]'': The war began. |- | 1918 || 18 November || An independent Latvia was proclaimed. |- | 1919 || || [[Latvian ruble]] currency introduced.<ref name="Berlin2006">{{cite book|author=Howard M. Berlin|title=World Monetary Units: An Historical Dictionary, Country by Country|year= 2006|publisher=McFarland |location=USA |isbn=978-0-7864-4042-9 |chapter=Latvia: Chronology |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_7XwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 }}</ref> |- | 1920 || 11 August || The [[Latvian–Soviet Peace Treaty]] was signed. |- | 1921 || 22 September || Latvia became a member of the [[League of Nations]]. |- | 1922 || February || A Latvian constitution was adopted. |- | 1934 || 15 May || Prime Minister [[Kārlis Ulmanis]] took power in a bloodless ''coup d'état''. |- | 1939 || 23 August || The [[Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact]] was signed between the [[Soviet Union|Soviet Union (USSR)]] and [[Nazi Germany]]. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 1940 || 16 June || An ultimatum was presented by the [[Soviet Union|USSR]] to Latvia. |- | 17 June || ''[[Soviet occupation of Latvia in 1940]]'': Soviet troops occupied the country. |- | 5 August || Latvia was incorporated into the [[Soviet Union]], becoming the Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic (SSR). |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1941 || 13 June || The first mass deportations of [[Latvian people|Latvians]] to various sites in the [[Soviet Union]] began. |- | 1 July || ''[[Occupation of Latvia by Nazi Germany]]'': [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] troops occupied [[Riga]]. |- | 1944 || October || ''[[Occupation of Latvia by Soviet Union 1944-1945]]'': The Soviet army reentered [[Riga]]. |- | 1955 || || About thirty thousand deportees returned to Latvia from the [[Soviet Union|USSR]] under a general amnesty. |- | 1981 || || The modern [[Vanšu Bridge]] was opened across the [[Daugava River]] in [[Riga]]. |- | 1987 || 14 June || The first demonstration in [[Riga]] to commemorate the 1941 deportations took place. |- | 1988 || 23 August || Mass demonstrations took place against the [[Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact]]. |- | 1990 || 4 May || The Latvian SSR Supreme Council adopted the declaration [[On the Restoration of Independence of the Republic of Latvia]]. |- | rowspan="3" valign="top" | 1991 || January || ''[[The Barricades]]'': Pro-[[Communist Party of Latvia|Communist]] political forces attempted to restore Soviet power in Latvia. |- | 6 September || The [[Soviet Union]] recognized Latvian independence. |- | 17 September || Latvia became a member of the United Nations. |}
== 21st century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 2004 || 2 April || Latvia became a member of [[NATO]]. |- | 1 May || Latvia became a member of [[European Union]]. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 2014 || 1 January || Latvia became a member of [[Eurozone]]. |}
